text:
meet the girls behind the blog! 
survivor and mother of two dog-ters. as as a self taught artist, delonÃ© did not pick up a paintbrush until 2009. it was trauma that pushed her creative outlet and in it, she found healing. she found a voice. among many other struggles, growing up bi-racial and searching for her identity has led her to embrace of human skin in her work. most of her subject matter comes from a place of dealing with her identity, childhood trauma, sexual abuse, and surviving an abusive relationship later in life. however, she wants people to see their own pain and healing through her work. she is a firm believer in cultivating healthy habits to deal with trauma and wants to help others do the same. yes, this road has been hard but she is thankful for the seasons and people who got her here. even the â€œmistakes.â€ the main thing she wants people to take away is you are not alone, it does get better, and there is a way to find gratitude even when it seems as though everything is crumbling around you. 
#donteatcandy

text:
power tables are made of white men and women
.

i think this is michelle obama's form of "#nameyourracist, which was *the* most amazing "game" on social media ever. there are too many for her to mention so she just said, "everyone in american 'power', ever. all at once"
.

and i'd like to do something rare (syke!) and compare this to my journey post book rejection! because i immediately stepped down, asking for explanations on weak (i said "sucky") parts, and bc there were any (yes there were but to quote mrs. obama, "they're just not smart" and missed them), so i got one line: "you spoke about the drawbacks of american health care" ...when i hve the approval in writing. not smart
.

literally? there is no "top", it's all just white people jacking off to monitory struggle, like the health care gap
.

and i think that was the real reason my ex-husband was pushed over the edge -- and i mean it; i'm not being ironic here. he expected something "behind the curtain-ish" and bc there isn't anything he couldn't properly reconcile his intellect against his fixed poverty. im mean, he was a janitor, but very much a genius. he thought he would find something that could match his elegance, but there really wasn't anything but more lazy ass terrorist white people
.

he cussed my mother out about it, which wasn't fair but i feel him. she has the kind of racialized blindness that is so subtle its caught in the air, and it will choke the shit out you the more you breath it in
.

and it was about tesla. he loves tesla and she was being dismissive and he just got at her. to everyone else at the table it was "liza, i'm not going to tell you to get a divorce, but that was not normal" but to me i was like "#twinning!" .

life is weird the closer you get to the top. you realize that all the "top" is made from is more money, which is the hight of manipulation, bc money is the weakest global currancy. like *all white people* (except anderson cooper) are the first victims of horizontal mobility. like, the same tired ass psychology, just now as "president"
.

america is incredibly unimpressive, which is why i just say whatever i please when *forced* to deal with the people behind it
.

text:
had a beautiful screening in santa monica. over 70 students showed up to see the film from all different backgrounds.

we had a powerful q and a after the film talking about how to combat trafficking, lgbtq rights, women's rights, assault, trauma, the filmmaking progress, how to be a mentor to youth, and actions to take right away to combat child trafficking. 
california's forgotten children documentary gives audiences a valuable understanding of commercial sexual exploitation through the voices of survivors and advocates in the movement. it is a proud feeling walking out of a screening knowing that the film inspired some people on their own journeys to create change in the world.

here is a picture of director melody miller, and faculty marla leech and sharyn obsatz from the journalism and film studies department at santa monica college. 
thank you for sharing the film at your school. looking forward to more collaborations in the future! â¤ï¸ .

join calililiindiesâ„¢ movement : #supporttheartsustaintheartistâ„¢ 
indie artists are navigating a marketplace in which rich corporations claim the word " indie " in order 2 capitalize on it's connotations

all too easy to relegate the #noncorporate #diy artist + art to an irrelevant corner of our societies - pretending that what we do is not work - truth is - "artist rights" are indeed 'human rights.'
the way artists are treated in any society, is a direct reflection of the 'humanity' ( or inhumanity ) at the very foundations of civilization . 
history and #herstory show that cultures which elevate wealth and forms of "feudalism" / corporate greed - are simply depriving and ultimately dooming themselves to lack-luster, soulless futures on every level, including economic failure ... while #civilizations who encourage and support the thriving, not just surviving of their citizens who are living artists, are healthy nourished - balanced and whole on every level - including a respect for #wildlife #nature #ecological systems as well as human needs such as healthcare #education #socialjustice

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still, today, right now.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the fake content - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking a real responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

a non

text:
@speakerryan @nyt.fi @nyjah @nyrangers @nypl @nyknicks @nytcooking bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

for me, tattooing is a way for me to heal and connect with my ancestry and myself. that is why i tattoo and why i choose to be tattooed. the process of tattooing is so important to me as a queer, transgender person of color. i want to share that healing with others, i want to share my story with others. because we are not alone in our own suffering. i want you to know that iâ€™m here and i see you and that itâ€™s okay.

thank you for supporting me, i will keep doing what i do.
.

text:
i am a person who doesn't believe in being a part of big groups. a person who is pretty much full of herself and don't feel the need to have a "social circle" to party on weekends. i have learnt the secret art of being content with my ownself, hence i usually avoid social gatherings until they are useful to me or my work.  my work makes me surrounded with hundreds of people everyday, i don't run away from that part but yes, i always find an escape from seasonal friendships and unreal presence of people.
â€¢
the difference between these two facts about me is, a conserved person as i am, when it comes to giving a special pedestal in my life, that i call friendship; i value the commitment as i value the presence of parents in my life. that's why i can't losely call someone my friend. 
here, she is that one person who constantly reminds me that i'm not a psycho or grumpy adult who is always unhappy to see people around haha.
since college she has been my support system, be it motivating me for my abilities, boosting my confidence or just helping me out from "boy troubles" of life. she has been there. saved me from all the wrong decisions, also, became my partner in crime. my anchor to the uncontrolled ship which would have otherwise flown and crashed to the waves of uncertainties of ocean called life. 
she is restoring my faith in the word "friend" and trespassing my territories since a long time. she made me feel beautiful inside out. she restored my faith in friendship. â¤ï¸ she's radhika @radhika8901 â¤
.
.
- by charu @ecstatic_being .
.
................................................................
.
.
in these times of #metoo and stories of sexual harassment, there are also women and men around us who made us feel more beautiful, more confident and powerful from both inside and out. 
if there is such a person in your life who ever made you feel so about yourself then wait no longer and share your story too. let us pay a small tribute to her/him here @shespeaksforthechange.

we all need such people around us afterall, don't we?
(dm us your story or tag us in your post.)

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

i think there is a real difference  between "no means no" and "yes means yes". the first tends to set a precedent for  consent to be assumed rather than confirmed. sometimes, the aggressor can choose to ignore body language or subtle rejections, and the recipient for whatever reason may not be able to verbalize their discomfort in the moment. in either case, if someone is incapacitated in any way, they cannot give legal consent to physicality. â€¢
â€¢
a "no" is definitely ğŸ’¯ğŸ’¯ğŸ’¯a reason to stop, but without a "yes", it shouldn't be an automatic go! it is time that we all set a new standard for checking in with our partners. consent yesterday doesn't necessarily mean consent today; consent to first base does not imply a home run. if we ask the questions about desires and needs first, we have way less probability of dispute after the fact; this is how we build foundations for strong relationships. every physical interaction should always be a mutual understanding and reflection of respect, and silence or implication does not ever equal consent. get an answer before taking action. â€¢
â€¢

text:
a few months ago, amidst another jarring wave of national news, @kellywilt and i met to discuss our shared need to do something to help both ourselves and others who have experienced trauma. we wanted to create a space where people felt heard and seen, in a place where they would feel a sense of deep belonging, to heal. the soulshine retreat was born.
.
the soulshine retreat is a highly intentional weekend of healing in community. a place to safely share your story and soak up positivity and light. a haven in the mountains.
.
our vision is closer than ever to coming to life now. we will be hosting the first of two informational meetings at the ninth house tonight at 6 pm.
.
if you feel a call to join us, please see the link in our bio for lots more info, dm, or attend the meeting.
.
#healingincommunity #soulshine #sisterhood #bebrave #brenebrown #womensretreat #shareyourstory #believesurvivors #metoo #tucsonaz #womenempoweringwomen #theninthhouse

text:
ğŸ‘‡ğŸ˜
dear wrongdoer,
it was humiliating.
what was it entirely? i thought again.
i couldn't name it. i didn't have words.
maybe sexting or one sided love or humiliation.
then, i named it opprobrium.
misunderstanding was the word given to me for not loving someone.
i was screaming but silently.
i was in pain but still smiling to hide it.
it felt as if i was alone & dying.
thus, causing me to untrust everyone around.
and so i trusted - "he that is low, has no pride."
i came to poetry to lessen this.
but this was a kind of intolerable complicity.
-from an ill-matched person you loved.

@poetrybypriyanshi via @priyanshi.jain05

text:
"many of us were raised to say yes. we're still learning how to say no, when so often our no goes unheard." in our boundaries issue, writer ilana masad discusses the importance of communication in relationships. "in recent months, the #metoo movement has exploded into prominence. with all its issuesâ€”its focus on white, wealthy, famous women, its early erasure of the originator of the hashtag, tarana burkeâ€”it has at least caused a larger swath of the population to talk about sexual harassment, assault, and the role of power. but something we don't talk about nearly often enough is how communication sits squarely in these dynamics as well." get the full story in anxy no. 3, available via link in bio. illustration by @nalghadban

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
a student from the missouri state university (msu) has been charged for allegedly raping a woman hours after she attended a #metoo rally in springfield over the weekend. according to a report by the , zachary alperin, 22, went to some bars with the victim after the rally ended, and then went to the womanâ€™s room on campus, per the court documents.
in her statement, the victim said that she allowed zachary to sleep in her room but told him not to touch her because she was drunk, the springfield news-leader reported. the woman told police that she fell asleep and woke up to find alperin lying naked on top of her. per the springfield news-leader, the woman â€œalleged that alperin performed sex acts on her and she pushed him away.â€
alperin allegedly confessed to performing sexual acts on the victim, as reported by the springfield news-leader. â€œi guess i tried to force myself on her, and i feel like such a terrible person for it,â€ the culprit told police. alperin is currently being held at the greene county jail on a bond of $20,000 following the investigation. he has been charged with second-degree rape and second-degree sodomy.
according to state law, if someone is convicted of rape and sodomy in the second degree, they can incur a maximum imprisonment of seven years, along with fines up to $10,000 for each offence. following the news, organizers of the #metoo rally in springfield expressed their shock at the incident and said that they have been â€œdevastatedâ€ by the news. however, they appreciated that the victim mustered the courage to report the rape, a report by said.
â€œwe are devastated. the thought that someone would leave our rally feeling so encouraged, just to be raped a few hours laterâ€¦ it is almost too much,â€ the organizers wrote in a facebook post, as quoted by nbc news. â€œif the woman who attended our rally that the article is referring to sees this, please know this: we are so proud of you for your bravery in coming forward. we are so sorry. we believe you. this was not your fault in any way. we are here for you,â€ it further read.

text:
steve smith joined us as the musical guest on a dark day in american history. while we engaged the pop oracle at the record co. in boston, massachusetts, several hundred miles to the south dr. christine blasey ford and brett kavanaugh testified before congress. this terrible spectacle informed my question and one more, later in the show. we may still be too close to the trauma of this day to want to spend 8 musical divinations micro focusing on it, and i get that. i also trust this format to such a degree that i can absolutely promise you this is a document of that day and, when we have a better sense of the full context and impact of it, we will marvel at how much was revealed here.  @stevesmithmusic @therecordcotrc @andrasjones  @aldouscollins @jj_gonson_photo @anajane9 @quinnyquinquinnnn #synchronicity @starburnsind @starburnsaudio #boston #metoo #brettkavanaugh #christineblaseyford #reverselysistrata

text:
@helsinginsanomat @helsinginratsupoliisi @nyt.fi @nytimestravel @nytimesfashion @mynytimes @nytimes wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
@helsinginsanomat @helsinkipoliisi @nyt.fi @nytimestravel @nytimesfashion @mynytimes @nytimes 
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies. 
they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
it was late last night - we were already in bed - when we got the message that a friend of jarens passed away.
.
i did not know this individual so whole he sat and watched a video of this mans life i laid next to him.
.
as pictures of this man and his family filled jarens screen i listened to the instrumental music play and the rain that was tapping softly against our windows and i thought about my own family.
.
it was one of those spiritual moments when life seems to slow down and everything that you thought mattered no longer seems relevant and you get a glimpse into how much god loves you, how much he loves your family. how much you love your family! and you know right then that they are what is important. youâ€™ve always known that of course, but in this moment you feel it!
.
so hold your loved ones today (including your teenagers who act like they donâ€™t want it) because families are pretty awesome, arenâ€™t they?!?! i am so very grateful for mine and each and every day i get to spend with them! â™¥ï¸

"gender based violence (gbv) is a global health, human rights and development issue that transcends geography, class, culture, age, race and religion to affect every community and country in every corner of the world. the article 1 of un declaration on the elimination of violence 1993 provides a definition of gender - based abuse, calling it "any act of gender - based violence that results in, or is likely to result in, physical, sexual or psychological harm or suffering to women, including threats of such acts, coercion or arbitrary deprivation of liberty, whether occurring in public or in private lifeâ€. in india, gender based violence has many manifestations; from the more universally prevalent forms of domestic and sexual violence including rape, to harmful practices such as, dowry, honour killings, acid attacks, witch - hunting, sexual harassment, child sexual abuse, trafficking for commercial sexual exploitation, child marriage, sex selective abortion, sati etc.
.
ministry of women and child development, has formulated a centrally sponsored scheme for setting up one stop centre, a sub-scheme of umbrella scheme for national mission for empowerment of women including indira gandhi mattritav sahyaog yojana.Â popularly known as sakhi, theÂ scheme is being implemented since 1st april 2015.Â these centres are being established across the country to provide integrated support and assistance under one roof to women affected by violence, both in private and public spaces in phased manner." .

we have to be willing to have uncomfortable conversations if things are going to change. i know miami isnâ€™t usually the place to have this moments but without our presence in these spaces we will continue to only scratch the surface. 
we must be willing to unearth these monstrous problems and deal with them directly instead of allowing them to stay buried, festering, rotting, and infecting us all. 
we must be brave. we must work to dismantle the patriarchal silence that blankets sexual violence against all people. silence is what holds us down. silence is the bedfellow of oppression. â€¢

we must be willing to uneah these monstrous problems and deal with them directly instead of allowing them to stay buried, festering, rotting, and infecting us all. 
we must be brave. we must work to dismantle the patriarchal silence that blankets sexual violence against all people. silence is what holds us down. silence is the bedfellow of oppression. â€¢

@speakerryan @nyt.fi @nyjah @nyrangers @nypl @nyknicks @nytcooking bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
steel
how does one find oneâ€™s steel?
one has to forge it! 
if one understands that we are ultimately always in a raw stateâ€¦. like a newborn!  we can start anew at any given moment.â€¦.. we can begin to eliminate our impuritiesâ€¦â€¦ our negative thoughts and emotionsâ€¦. our bad habitsâ€¦. and become aware of the narratives we play and replay in our minds. similar to the process of steel making we must take on  high heat (challenges and seemingly impossible tasks) and embrace adversity. we must take these on willingly. that is where we begin to forge our steel. the very high heatâ€¦.. repeated action of pounding, grinding and sharpening. this repeated actionâ€¦â€¦ dailyâ€¦â€¦. is what one needs. 
this is hard! 
itâ€™s hard workâ€¦.. relentless work and brutal honesty with oneself. 
one knows when one is ready. itâ€™s a whisper at firstâ€¦â€¦and then the whisper gets louder and can no longer be ignored. we canâ€™t silence that constant chatter in our mind! thats when one asksâ€¦â€¦ â€˜ why am i feeling thisâ€¦â€¦ dissatisfaction?â€™
that is the time to begin the search for the true meaning and purpose of oneâ€™s existence. that process is finding ( forging ) your steel.
â€¢asl notebooks, 2008 @asleninde

text:
what would happen if instead of using pain to cripple us.. we used pain as power.
.
.
to empower us. to make actual change in this world & use our voices.
.
.
the ones who do.. are the ones who make the greatest impact. .
.
because once you turn your pain into power.. you become unstoppable. a warrior not a victim.
.
.
and nothing will break you.

life sentence for medically kidnapped christian activist professor solange martinez at nyc bronx central hospital
december 5, 2018 daniel j leach jr 
please help save medically kidnapped christian activist professor solange martinez who got life sentence in psychiatric hospital with forced.medication.
solange martinez is being held at north central hospital in the bronx . she Â has been advocating for the poor and has been successfull in helping people in the court system . she has had several victories against the nyc social services agencies when they committed fraud . she is not an attorney and for that reason the legal system feels threatened by her . if everyone started representing themselves and others , it would take away billions of dollars from Â the attorneys , judges , police , courts , prisons , transport companies , hospitals , doctors , nurses , social workers , certified public accountants , maintence workers , food service providers , cleaning services , security agents , internet providers , computer technicians , and all their supporting staff , buisness and corporations . so they locked her up . they are trying to silence her with a 60 year sentence and forced medication which has already begun . the drugs include : halidol , zolpidan , lithium carbonate and others . she is already getting tired and dizzy . a witness to her abduction heard officers of the nypd from precinct 52 say : 'we have determined that no crime has been committed here , the emt's are going to take you.' the emt stated : 'you can sue us later' . witnesses heard the chief of security at jacoby hospital , where the hearing was held , make the following statement : 'you are not here because you are mentally ill . you are here because you think your so smart .' also please help by calling the rutherford institute on solange martinezâ€™s behalf.

text:
sexism, this word is still viewed as a â€œbadâ€ word. how dare i point out the reality that still remains alive and well in 2018!! first, letâ€™s define sexism: a type of discrimination that undervalues, belittles, and treats a certain gender, often women, differently from the opposite gender. sexism may be conscious or unconscious, intentional or unintentional, and can impact peopleâ€™s work.  we are expected to stay docile and polite and respond affirmatively regardless of the circumstances. this my friends is sexism!  in order to eradicate this behavior we must stand united. standing idly by watching another female stand alone in her attempt to correct inequality will only extend our anti-discrimination efforts. the effect of, â€œevery women for her selfâ€ mentality is disastrous for our path to equality.  imagine for a moment, a world where all women support each other.  i, for one, refuse to ignore the challenges and double standards we face.
â€œeach time a woman stands up for herself, without knowing it possibly, without claiming it, she stands up for all women.â€ ~ maya angelou

text:
@speakerryan @nyt.fi @nyjah @nyrangers @nypl @nyknicks @nytcooking bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

@speakerryan @nyt.fi @nyjah @nyrangers @nypl @nyknicks @nytcooking in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

text:
@speakerryan @nyt.fi @nyjah @nyrangers @nypl @nyknicks @nytcooking - bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
@speakerryan @nyt.fi @nyjah @nyrangers @nypl @nyknicks @nytcooking this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
@speakerryan @nyt.fi @nyjah @nyrangers @nypl @nyknicks @nytcooking bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
@speakerryan @nyt.fi @nyjah @nyrangers @nypl @nyknicks @nytcooking - bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
@speakerryan @nyt.fi @nyjah @nyrangers @nypl @nyknicks @nytcooking bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin

@speakerryan @uutisjousi @radiosuomi @radiosuomipop @foxnews @huffpostrelationships @huffpostcaliving @miamiherald @burgerking @cnn @abcnews
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
how you handle your abuser is up to you.
thereâ€™s a lot of misinformation circling around about what survivors can and canâ€™t do in the aftermath of narcissistic abuse.  as a grown adult, itâ€™s up to you what you do.  or donâ€™t do.  there are no set rules, as long as you donâ€™t break the law.
.
.
.
many say you have to simply ignore what your abuser did to you, accept your fate and do nothing.
they say that â€œliving well is the best revenge.â€
but, not everyone wants revenge.  revenge against an emotionally immature, mentally ill non-person is petty and itâ€™s focusing on the abuser.  some of us want justice.
.
.
.
getting #justice for myself  played a key part in my healing.  i went from being manipulated by the abuser to seeing him as the spineless little bitch he really is, in just a matter of weeks.  any lingering trauma bonding has been absolutely smashed to smithereens.  the only feelings i have left towards this individual are pity, and a degree of contempt.
.
.
.
as is typical with these passive-aggressive individuals, the narc made all kinds of pathetic threats.  he was going to sue me for refusing an abortion.  he was going to report me to the cops for posting about my abuse experiences on instagram.  he thought he could silence me by trying to project his own vile qualities onto me, in a series of illiterate, angry emails.  none of it worked.
i refused to listen to individuals who told me stuff like: â€œbut itâ€™s not your fault.  they are great manipulators.â€ or â€œitâ€™s best not to cross them.  you donâ€™t know what they are capable of.â€
i took my power back by fighting back.
.
.
.

iâ€™m not talking about engaging in direct arguments or any form of direct contact with this disturbed individual.  that would be an utter waste of time and energy.
iâ€™m talking about changing the power dynamics. 
i let this pathetic excuse for a man know, in a variety of ways, that if he ever tries to cross me in any way, ever again, heâ€™s finished.  completely #cancelled.  and the narcissist knows iâ€™m not playing. and neither are my loved ones.  and neither is the judicial system, for that matter. .
.
.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

text:
@huffposttaste @foxnews @nytimes in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
@huffposttaste @foxnews @nytimes in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
@huffposttaste @foxnews @nytimes bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
dec 8 // a note she wrote on mint // celebrating 24 teas of christmas // our parents gave great parties and back then, the very best always led to three things â€“ boney m being played till the amp exploded; slices of black forest cake flung against an exposed brick wall; and the detritus of a table including opened yet, uneaten boxes of red tulip after dinner mints. for two small girls, chocolate covered toothpaste was the equivalent of ecstasy. we were good at sneaking, my sister and i, and our hungover parents were good at sleeping and this combination found us tiptoeing down the shag pile, past their door, across the slate floor of the kitchen and round the corner to the billiards room, where our table converted into a dining space for twenty. it was here two small, forensic scientists would discover morning-after evidence of the night before. vinyl records strewn, cigarette ash, the aforementioned flung cherries and cream of â€˜cake on the wallâ€™ (years later weâ€™d discover this was a game where instead of throwing knives, they threw cake, at an outstretched woman in her underwear â€“ yep wtf â€“ that was 1978 for you). and then, the wonder of it all - glamourous chocolates in tiny crinkly, black sleeves. it always amazed - how could grown-ups demonstrate such restraint as to leave such delight behind on the table? how could they not want to fill their pockets? and weâ€™d fit as many as we could into our tiny hands before lying in humming silence on our backs under the table with our feet jammed up and weâ€™d eat red tulips after dinner mints until we were practically sick. my record was 14. 
#tea2 #adventcalendar #christmas #tea #australia #afterdinnermints #love #sisters #1978 #party #empowermentÂ #boneym #metoo #t2tea

text:
ieder jaar helpen we honderden kinderen en jongeren uit nederlanden die te maken hebben gehad met huiselijk geweld, verwaarlozing en uitbuiting. zij groeien vaak op in armoede of in situaties waarbij het vieren van een verjaardag, het volgen van zwemles, het dragen van een warme jas en het meedoen aan sociale activiteiten niet vanzelfsprekend is.â €
â €
we vragen je een donatie te doen en 4 mensen uit je omgeving te motiveren om dat ook te doen. als zij op hun beurt ook 4 mensen vragen te doneren en zij vervolgens hetzelfde doen, zorgen we samen voor een positieve toekomst voor deze kinderen. je kunt ook een eigen inzamelingsactie starten of je familieleden, vrienden en collega's vertellen over onze campagne.â €
â €

text:
dec 8 // a note she wrote on mint // celebrating 24 teas of christmas // our parents gave great parties and back then, the very best always led to three things â€“ boney m being played till the amp exploded; slices of black forest cake flung against an exposed brick wall; and the detritus of a table including opened yet, uneaten boxes of red tulip after dinner mints. for two small girls, chocolate covered toothpaste was the equivalent of ecstasy. we were good at sneaking, my sister and i, and our hungover parents were good at sleeping and this combination found us tiptoeing down the shag pile, past their door, across the slate floor of the kitchen and round the corner to the billiards room, where our table converted into a dining space for twenty. it was here two small, forensic scientists would discover morning-after evidence of the night before. vinyl records strewn, cigarette ash, the aforementioned flung cherries and cream of â€˜cake on the wallâ€™ (years later weâ€™d discover this was a game where instead of throwing knives, they threw cake, at an outstretched woman in her underwear â€“ yep wtf â€“ that was 1978 for you). and then, the wonder of it all - glamourous chocolates in tiny crinkly, black sleeves. it always amazed - how could grown-ups demonstrate such restraint as to leave such delight behind on the table? how could they not want to fill their pockets? and weâ€™d fit as many as we could into our tiny hands before lying in humming silence on our backs under the table with our feet jammed up and weâ€™d eat red tulips after dinner mints until we were practically sick. my record was 14. @t2tea

text:
@speakerryan @burgerking_suomi @yleuutisluokka @maddowshow @arimelber @lastwordmsnbc @katyturnbc @stephruhle wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
@stephruhle @uutisjousi @huffpostqueervoices @foxnews @mcdonaldsmalaysia @miamiherald @cnn 
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

emma charlotte duerre watson is an english actress, model, and activist.
as one of the leaders of the un women heforshe campaign, watson has changed the global conversation about feminism today. 
watson has used her household name to lead nonprofits, ethical brands & critical movements into the mainstream.

in her every endeavor she plays to her continuous humanitarian evolvement, she encourages young men & women with privilege and power to ask themselves - if not me, then who? if not now, when? 
as the youngest a-lister as un women goodwill ambassador, she exemplifies the potential young influencers have in the pursuit of global good.

text:
i am humbled to be able to lead an organization that has such a profound impact on our direct community. jida@refugeelink.com  for more ways to be a part of the change ************************************ ***ğŸ‡ºğŸ‡¸ dear supporters,
on behalf of the amaanah board, i am pleased to announce that jida nabulsi will be joining amaanah refugee servicesâ€™ team as the chief executive officer. her leadership will be effective december 10th, 2018. 
jida joins us with over a decade of strategic marketing experience in the oil and gas industry, most recently as a senior analyst at exterran in houston. there, she was forecasting trends, managing budgetary tasks, and spearheading company-wide goals and initiatives. 
her decision to leave the corporate world was driven by her passion to lead a community service organization and serve resettled refugees. as a hands-on supporter for over nine years and developer of our signature pink & blue refugee family event, jida will be a great fit as we continue to uphold our promise to the resettled refugee community.

she brings with her the organizational skills, strategy development and company branding experience that will confidently pave a path forward in strengthening our mission to integrate resettled refugees into their new homes and communities. 
jida has a bachelorâ€™s degree in finance and economics from the university of st. thomas and is certified in marketing strategy from cornell university. she is currently pursuing an mba from texas a&m university. 
as we turn the page from our 10-year anniversary, we are very excited to welcome jida as our new ceo.

sincerely,

roger yelton

chairman of the board

text:
#queercore started when someone told me that i couldn't sing songs using she vs. he pronouns at their venue. one letter of the alphabet, an "s", and singing my own songs, would keep me from playing music and making a living like so many others. bump that! i created a stage for all of us, and no one needs to be silenced. queercore brings storytellers and gives folks space to tell their own! book us at your school! 
i am also looking for more artists to share/host a stage! let's talk! 
i am excited to put more dates on the calendar in 2019! #teachingartist #artsed #highered #speaker #performingarts #openmic #storyteller #share #commmunity #lgbtq #glbtq #queer #collegespeaker #baltimore #philadelphia #wheeling #pittsburgh #qpoc #poc #metoo #timesup #resist #imagine #booking #shebelievedshecouldsoshedid

text:
@regran_ed from @queenofpettysjt -  @regran_ed from @unheardvoicesmag -  a woman who was 16 when she killed a #nashville man who solicited her for sex must serve at least 51 years in prison before sheâ€™s eligible for release, according to the #tennessee supreme court.

on thursday the court said defendants like #cyntoiabrown , who are convicted of first-degree murder committed after july 1, 1995 and sentenced to life imprisonment, canâ€™t become eligible for release from prison before serving more than five decades.

thursdayâ€™s ruling came in response to a lawsuit in which brown argues her sentence is unconstitutional, citing a 2012 opinion by the us supreme court that said mandatory life sentences without parole for juvenile offenders violate the us constitution.

the #tennesseesupremecourt explained in a statement that â€œunder state law, a life sentence is a determinate sentence of 60 years. however, the sixty-year sentence can be reduced by up to 15 percent, or 9 years, by earning various sentence credits.â€ a district court previously denied brownâ€™s motion, per court documents, pointing out she hadnâ€™t been sentenced to life in prison without the possibility of parole â€” just a life sentence.

the case is pending judgment by the sixth circuit court of appeals, which asked the tennessee supreme court to share its opinion.

more than a decade after sentencing, brownâ€™s case caught the attention of a-list celebrities like #rihanna and #kimkardashianwest who began advocating for mercy. her story spread on social media using the hashtag #freecyntoiabrown 
brown says she was forced into prostitution after a difficult childhood. at her trial, she said her victim, #johnnymitchellallan , solicited her for sex and drove her to his house.

there, brown saw a gun cabinet in allanâ€™s room, she said during her trial. she resisted him until he appeared to reach under the bed, at which point she believed he was going to kill her. brown took a gun out of her purse and shot allan, killing him.

in a clemency hearing in may, the tennessee board of parole was split on its recommendation to gov. bill haslam. two of the six member voted to grant clemency, two to deny it, and two to make

text:
i am not
self
made
i am made by bowed heads and bloody knees 
chained hands and thrashed backs
bruises and love, pain and sacrifice on my behalf
i am hands lifting and pulling me
a village surrounding me
a tribe fighting for me
a god protecting me, forgiving me, keeping me
nay sayers, cheerleaders, champions and weapons drawn against me
i am made by the constant fight for black skinned justice
the screams of pain from me too â€˜cause #metoo
lessons from classrooms with hands raised and guns so violent even with... hands raised
all the pain made me, laughter made me, my mama made me, my husband made me, my sons made me, my teachers made me, my sisters made me
i was made with a pen in my hand, gun in my hand fighting for  someone elseâ€™s land 
i am bold, brilliant, successful and proud. i am humble, grateful and blessed. i am all these things and more things but i didnâ€™t make me. iâ€™m so many people, places and things within me. with a god tied bow around me. 
i am not

text:
december 7, 1941. on that day in history, 2,403 american lives were lost. to most people this is a number. but each and every single one of those numbers; 1 through 2,403, was an individual life, an individual spirit. and each of those lost lives affected hundreds of others. as humans, we naturally go about day to day, with expectations and assumptions of what will happen. in other words, we donâ€™t expect the unexpected. because of this, many people donâ€™t truly think about how thankful they are for those around them. we donâ€™t truly understand how grateful we are for someone until weâ€™ve lost them. the families, friends, and loved ones that lost those that mattered most to them on that fateful day, likely woke up with the expectation that they would see them. but life does not follow a pattern, nor does it meet expectations. men and women of great spirit were lost on this day, so long ago. but we rose up as a nation and as one people. 4 years later, japan wished they had never touched foot on american soil. when we come together as one nation, and as one people, we can do great things. when we are thankful, even for those that seem like our enemies, we become stronger than the fear or hate that separates is. so when you wake up in the morning, be thankful, even for the people that may not be thankful for you. when you love your enemy as yourself, great things can be accomplished and great men and women can rise up. this is america.

december 7, 1941. on that day in history, 2,403 american lives were lost. to most people this is a number. but each and every single one of those numbers; 1 through 2,403, was an individual life, an individual spirit. and each of those lost lives affected hundreds of others. as humans, we naturally go about day to day, with expectations and assumptions of what will happen. in other words, we donâ€™t expect the unexpected. because of this, many people donâ€™t truly think about how thankful they are for those around them. we donâ€™t truly understand how grateful we are for someone until weâ€™ve lost them. the families, friends, and loved ones that lost those that mattered most to them on that fateful day, likely woke up with the expectation that they would see them. but life does not follow a pattern, nor does it meet expectations. men and women of great spirit were lost on this day, so long ago. but we rose up as a nation and as one people. 4 years later, japan wished they had never touched foot on american soil. when we come together as one nation, and as one people, we can do great things. when we are thankful, even for those that seem like our enemies, we become stronger than the fear or hate that separates is. so when you wake up in the morning, be thankful, even for the people that may not be thankful for you. when you love your enemy as yourself, great things can be accomplished and great men and women can rise up. this is america.

text: most know... i am very open about my sexual assault. tonight i took a huge step and sent him a letter. but i was scared, more so than i thought was possible... i mean, this was 15 years ago and i truly thought i had most of my emotions secure when it came to this. but i realized that talking about it factually and actually feeling it while talking about it emotionally are two very... very different things. it took me awhile to send it because i kept having major panic attacks. this was my reaction right before sending it, but i did it... and i got my voice. he finally gets to hear what i couldn't say as a child and now... i feel calm. #rapesurvivor #survivors #assault #metoo

text:
from @gshrudayana -  the mirror never lies adalah film fiksi arahan kamila andini pada tahun 2011. tahun ini datang kesempatan untuk kita menontonnya bersama sama!

hari: sabtu, 8 desember 2018
jam: registrasi dibuka mulai pukul 16.00 wita 
venue: lantai 2 warung @menbrayut
.
"clothes aren't going to change the world. the women who wear them will."
.
ada keterkaitan antara ruang hidupmu (lingkungan) dengan kehidupan juga penghidupan. fashion, baik baju maupun perhiasan adalah industri penghasil limbah yang besar bagi lingkungan. myra juliarti (desainer @akusiji) dan dian suri (desainer @kunangjewelry) memiliki kesamaan semangat dalam mengawali bisnisnya agar bertanggung jawab bagi lingkungan dan sosial.

ada cerita apa saja dari mereka? bagaimana tantangan yang ada dan apakah ada harapan terwujudnya revolusi fashion di masa kini?

dengarkan semuanya di #hearmetoo session setelah pemutaran. yuk berakhir pekan bersama enam belas film festival bali!

festival ini gratis dengan komitmen zerowaste, jadi bawa tumbler/botol minumnya ya!

#hearmetoo #metoo #gerakbersama #hapuskekerasanseksual #enambelasffest #enambelasffestbali #saveibunuril #zerowasteevent #zerowastebali - #regrann

plante suggests being as specific as possible when you ask. we often refer to our mental struggles in vague terms because we donâ€™t want to disclose too much in the workplace, but perhaps if your boss knew you were using the afternoon to recharge in the outdoors or go to a therapy appointment, she could become less skeptical of what the day actually means to you. also, work on phrasing the request to let your manager know that youâ€™re taking this time so you can come back mentally stronger, refreshed, and in a better place to be productive at work.

that being said, â€œmental health days can help in the short term, but they might not help in the long term if thereâ€™s a bigger problem to be addressed,â€ plante says. â€œa day off can help, but it also might be indicative of a larger issue,â€ he says, and if you suspect thatâ€™s the case, itâ€™s better to consult with a therapist.

text:
ahhhhhh! this soup! itâ€™s my go to comfort dinner when itâ€™s cold outside and it has been cold here in dallas.
.
this soup is also easy, fast (start to finish is 30 min), and delicious. seriously, i have yet to meet anyone who doesnâ€™t love this soup! #asoulsurvivormeals
.
hereâ€™s the other thing about this soup, it has no name! i told my husband i wanted to call it carrot chowder and he was like ğŸ¤¢. he then suggested halloween soup since we always have it for dinner on halloween but i didnâ€™t love that. so we have yet to find a name for it! ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚ if you have any awesome ideas leave them in the comments section!
.
please ... do not be scared away by the carrots in this soup. i am 100% serious when i say everyone likes this soup! .
- 1lb lean ground beef (93/7)
- 4 cups tomato juice
- 2 cans cream of celery
- 1 1/2 cups water
- 1 tsp garlic salt
- 1 tsp pepper
- 2 cups shredded carrots. i buy large carrots and shred them but you can buy the pre shredded carrots if youâ€™d rather. .
1. in a large pot brown hamburger over medium heat and drain.
2. all all other ingredients and stir to combine.
3. turn heat up to high and allow soup to come to a boil.
4. reduce heat to low/medium and let simmer for 20 minutes making sure to stir occasionally. serves 6. cal: 224 c: 17.9 f: 7.9 p: 18.3

so here is part of my story. itâ€™s not pretty and itâ€™s sometimes too real, but itâ€™s mine. i was humbled, scared, and excited when @jendeanphoto asked me to share my story on her podcast, the gardenia project (itâ€™s recently made the @mainepublic short list of podcasts!). itâ€™s a storytelling podcast with portraits of strong women to show that we are resilient, and that there is usually more to anyone than what is seen on the outside. in the newest episode, i share a story that iâ€™ve kept hidden for years, but am beginning to share more and more because it is a part of me. it is intense; and i feel humbled, scared and excited again today. itâ€™s not something iâ€™d typically share with my clients, but iâ€™m sharing in hopes of showing that we can heal and be whole no matter what happens. light is always more powerful than darkness. ....
....
there is a trigger warning for those with sexual assault pasts, but i will say that there are not many details. we focused on the healing journey rather than the trauma. ....
....

text:
meeting the dalai lama with nkt survivors (part 4)

by erika adler (continued from part 3)........it was time for our meeting to end, but hh seemed unwilling to leave us. he told carol that she and jeremy, one of his aides, should talk about meeting up again in dharamsala. he invited us all to visit him there and told us he would remember us. he shook our hands again, embraced people, and pulled us all together for a group photograph, something i will always remember.

i had heard a great deal about the nkt from carol and other survivors, and seen footage of their noisy protests against hh, but until i was the o2 arena on saturday iâ€™d never seen them face to face. it felt disgusting, in the same way that visiting a broken toilet is disgusting. i knew it was going to stink, and it did.

but our meeting with the dalai lama has left an enduring impression on me of hope. it was incredibly reassuring to hear him tell us to go back to the original teachings of the buddha, which in my experience can so easily get lost under the many traditions and practices that are taught in the west. i donâ€™t know (yet) what others are feeling, but it now feels entirely possible that his effect on all of us will create ripples yet to be imagined... erika

text: if you have ever wondered about why the#metoo movement is important. if you have ever wondered why or how someone could be a serial abuser. if you have ever questioned a victim's story or found yourself rationalizing behavior that borders on abuse.... listen to the podcast series believed. it is not for the faint of heart and many moments are hard to listen to. but it is so important to hear and understand what happened in the case of larry nassar. it's important to know that there are times when we need to critically think about implicit trust, to know when to question what we know to be true, and to talk about things that seem wrong or out of place. hundreds of girls were abused because most didn't understand or didn't think they would be believed or spoke up and were shut down. but when the story was out and they knew they weren't alone, it all changed. they were validated. || abuse (sexual, emotional, physical, verbal) doesn't happen in a vacuum. it happens within the context of relationship, trust, and believing what we know to be true. an abuser's greatest protection is in causing their victim to question whether or not something is actually wrong and/or that they will be believed if they say anything. || let's strive to ask the right questions, listen for the answers, and critically approach the status quo. let's strive to see what we don't want to believe is true.... for the sake of ourselves and the generations to come.

text:
so for those who don't know, this has been a long time coming for me to post this officially. but a month or two ago, i wrote and submitted a poem for the possibility to be included in an anthology that talks about sexual harassment and sexual assault. i received an email from indie blu(e) who told me my poem was accepted to be included in the anthology. 
well, on december 1st, we will not be silenced: the lived experience of sexual harassment and sexual assault told powerfully through poetry, prose, essay, and art was published! i of course have already ordered and received a copy for myself and have taken some pictures of me, the anthology and some of my poem. i can't be any happier about this whole thing and have written a blog post about it, which can be seen here:  https://rainyday.blog/2018/12/07/why-we-will-not-be-silenced-the-lived-experience-of-sexual-harassment-and-sexual-assault-told-powerfully-through-poetry-prose-essay-and-art-is-important-to-me/

thank you everyone for being so supportive of me and my writing endeavors! please get the book if you can because proceeds go to sexual harassment and sexual assault survivors. #blog #post #important #wewillnotbesilenced #metoo #poetry #sexualharassment #sexualassault
